<Rewrite PAsource="" >THE </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >fiancee </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >of a Briton who died after a drunken assault near </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Sydney's Bondi beach </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >hit out bitterly yesterday after </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >his attacker was cleared of </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >killing him.
</Rewrite>

<New PAsource="" >Connie Casey </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >and relatives of </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >postman Brian Hagland. 23, wept as </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >a jury acquitted the man both of murder and manslaughter. </Rewrite>
<New PAsource="" >"I feel angry and cheated," said 26-year-old Connie. </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >"</Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >Everyone is just </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >torn apart."
</Verbatim>

<New PAsource="" >Brian's younger sister Jane said: "This is not justice for Brian, It is very painful for us all. I don't know how we are going to move on."
</New>

<New PAsource="" >Londoner Brian, cousin of EastEnders' star Sid Owen, was on holiday in Australia with Connie in September 1996. They planned to emigrate.
</New>

<Rewrite PAsource="" >They were walking home from a party when he was attacked by </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Aaron Lee Martin, 25</Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >.
</Rewrite>

<Rewrite PAsource="" >It was claimed </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Martin </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >tried to strangle </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Brian before pushing him </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >under a </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >bus </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >and kicking him in the face. </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Brian died in hospital </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >of multiple </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >injuries</Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >.
</Rewrite>

<New PAsource="" >Martin claimed he had no memory of the incident. </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >And after </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >the jury </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >had been out for six and a half days, </New>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >he was convicted only of </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >grievous bodily harm.
</Verbatim>

<New PAsource="" >He will be sentenced in six weeks' time by </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >New South Wales Supreme Court </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >and faces a maximum 25 years' jail.
</New>

<Rewrite PAsource="" >The dead man's </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >parents, Brian </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >Snr </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >and Shirley Hagland, </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >were distraught at the verdicts </Rewrite>
<New PAsource="" >after a month-long trial and will now fly home.
</New>

<New PAsource="" >Sister Jane said: 'We have waited three long years to see this man punished, and we are very shocked and disappointed
</New>

<New PAsource="" >"We saw Martin smile at his mother and shake his fists in the air. That was very hard, especially for my mother."
</New>

<New PAsource="" >The case was complicated by inconclusive forensic evidence and the lack of witnesees when Brian went under the bus.
</New>

<New PAsource="" >Fiancee Connie, of Cricklewood. north west London, was phoning for </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >help </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >at that moment from a nearby restaurant.
</New>

<New PAsource="" >She said yesterday: "I have struggled for nearly three years to reach this point, and it has taken everything inside me mentally, physically and emotionally."
</New>

<New PAsource="" >"I hope Martin gets the maximum sentence. Nothing can replace Brian."
</New>

<New PAsource="" >The judge had said she had "every sympathy" for Brian's loved ones.
</New>

<Rewrite PAsource="" >A second man, </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Sean Cushman, 25, was convicted of being an accessory </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >and also awaits sentence.
</Rewrite>



